32. Thymoetes: is mentioned in the Iliad, 111, 146, as one of the elders of Troy. A soothsayer had predicted that a child should be born on a certain day who should cause the destruction of Troy. On that day both Paris, the son of Priam, and Munippus, the son of Thymoetes, were born. Hence Priam, supposing the prophecy had reference to MunippuS, ordered both the infant and his mother, Cylla, to be put to death. AeneaS, therefore, is in doubt whether the advice of Thymoetes to carry the horse into the city is given out of resentment and treachery (dolo), or under the influence of sate (sic sata serebant).
